    <h2>1. What Is a Combi Oven?</h2>
    <p>A combi oven is a commercial oven that gives you three distinct cooking modes in a single appliance:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Convection Mode (Dry Heat):</strong> A powerful fan circulates hot air throughout the cavity, just like a standalone <a href="/blog/deck-oven-vs-convection-oven">convection oven</a>. Ideal for baking, roasting, gratinating, and finishing dishes that need crispy exteriors and even browning.</li>
      <li><strong>Steam Mode (100% Humidity):</strong> A built-in boiler or injection system generates steam inside the oven cavity. This is equivalent to having a separate commercial steamer. Perfect for steaming vegetables, fish, rice, idlis, dhokla, and reheating food without drying it out.</li>
      <li><strong>Combination Mode (Steam + Convection):</strong> This is where the magic happens. The oven simultaneously controls both heat and humidity levels, letting you set precise temperature (typically 30°C to 300°C) and humidity (0% to 100%) independently. This mode is what makes a combi oven irreplaceable — roasting chicken with crispy skin but juicy interiors, baking bread with perfect crust and soft crumb, or slow-cooking proteins at exact humidity levels.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The combi oven was invented in Germany in the 1970s. Today, it is the backbone of virtually every professional kitchen in Europe, North America, and increasingly across Asia. In India, adoption is growing rapidly — especially in 5-star hotels, chain restaurants, QSRs, airline catering, hospital kitchens, and modern cloud kitchens.</p>

