    <h2>4. How Steam Injection Works in a Combi Oven</h2>
    <p>Steam is what sets a combi oven apart from every other oven type. Understanding how it works will help you evaluate different brands and models.</p>

    <h3>Boiler-Based Steam Generation</h3>
    <p>Premium combi ovens (Rational, Convotherm, Alto-Shaam) use a dedicated boiler — a separate water heating chamber that generates consistent, high-volume steam. The boiler heats water independently of the oven cavity, meaning it can deliver steam at precise rates regardless of the oven temperature. Benefits include faster steam generation, more consistent humidity levels, and better steam quality. Boiler-based systems are more expensive and require descaling and water softener connections, but they deliver superior results for high-volume kitchens.</p>

    <h3>Injection-Based (Boilerless) Steam Generation</h3>
    <p>Mid-range and budget combi ovens spray water directly onto a heated element or the fan inside the oven cavity. The water instantly evaporates into steam. This is simpler, cheaper to manufacture, and requires less maintenance. However, steam quality and consistency can vary — especially when the oven door is opened frequently. Unox CHEFTOP uses an advanced version of this approach (their STEAM.Maxi technology) that delivers near-boiler-level performance without a traditional boiler.</p>

    <h3>Why Steam Matters for Indian Kitchens</h3>
    <p>Steam is not just for European-style cooking. In Indian commercial kitchens, steam mode is invaluable for: steaming idlis and dhokla in bulk, reheating biryani and rice dishes without drying them out, cooking tandoori chicken with juicy interiors, producing naan and kulcha with the right moisture, and bulk-cooking vegetables for banquets while retaining nutrients and colour.</p>

    <h2>5. Programmable Menus and Touchscreen Controls</h2>
    <p>Modern combi ovens are essentially computers attached to cooking chambers. Here is what the controls offer:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Multi-Step Programming:</strong> Set a recipe with multiple stages — e.g., Stage 1: Steam at 100°C for 5 minutes (to generate crust flexibility), Stage 2: Combination mode at 220°C with 40% humidity for 25 minutes, Stage 3: Dry convection at 230°C for 5 minutes (for browning). The oven transitions automatically between stages.</li>
      <li><strong>Recipe Libraries:</strong> Premium models come with 200–500+ pre-loaded recipes. The Rational iCombi Pro includes iCookingSuite — an AI-assisted system where you select the food type and desired result, and the oven automatically sets the parameters.</li>
      <li><strong>Core Probe Cooking:</strong> Insert a multi-point probe into the food. Set the target core temperature (e.g., 72°C for chicken), and the oven monitors in real time, adjusting temperature and humidity and alerting you when the food reaches the target. This eliminates guesswork and ensures food safety compliance.</li>
      <li><strong>Touchscreen Interface:</strong> High-resolution colour touchscreens with photo-based recipe selection. Staff with minimal training can operate the oven by selecting a photo of the dish they want to cook. This is critical for Indian kitchens with high staff turnover.</li>
      <li><strong>HACCP Data Logging:</strong> Automatic logging of cooking temperatures and times for food safety compliance. Essential for hotel chains, hospitals, and airline catering facilities that need documentation.</li>
      <li><strong>Cloud Connectivity:</strong> Premium models from Rational (ConnectedCooking) and Unox (Digital.ID) offer WiFi connectivity. Chefs can upload recipes to multiple ovens remotely, monitor cooking status from a phone, and receive maintenance alerts. Useful for QSR chains with standardised menus across multiple outlets.</li>
    </ul>

