    <h2>10. Applications: Who Should Buy a Combi Oven?</h2>

    <h3>Hotels and Banquet Kitchens</h3>
    <p>Hotels are the largest buyers of combi ovens in India. A 200-room hotel with banquet facilities typically needs at least two 20-tray combi ovens (or one 20-tray and two 10-tray units). The combi oven handles everything from breakfast buffet prep (steamed eggs, baked goods, grilled items) to banquet service (roasted meats, steamed vegetables, reheating) to room service. Many 5-star hotels in India use Rational iCombi Pro as their standard. The ROI is clear: one combi oven replaces a separate steamer, convection oven, and holding cabinet.</p>

    <h3>QSR Chains and Fast Casual Restaurants</h3>
    <p>QSR chains love combi ovens for their consistency. Programme the recipe once, and every outlet produces identical results regardless of cook skill level. Brands like Subway, KFC (for some menu items), and Indian chains use combi ovens with locked recipe programmes. A 6-tray combi oven is typically sufficient for a single QSR outlet. For more on QSR kitchen setup, see our <a href="/blog/restaurant-setup-cost-india">Restaurant Setup Cost India</a> guide.</p>

    <h3>Bakery and Bakery-Cafes</h3>
    <p>While dedicated <a href="/blog/commercial-oven-for-bakery">bakery ovens</a> (deck ovens, rack ovens) are better for bread-only production, a combi oven excels in bakery-cafes that also serve savoury items, grilled sandwiches, and hot meals. The steam mode produces excellent results for croissants, baguettes, and Danish pastries. Many premium bakery-cafes use a combi oven alongside a deck oven.</p>

    <h3>Cloud Kitchens</h3>
    <p>Space is at a premium in cloud kitchens. A single 6 or 10-tray combi oven can replace a convection oven, a steamer, and a holding cabinet — saving 2–3 square metres of kitchen space. For cloud kitchens running multiple brands from one kitchen, the programmable recipe feature ensures each brand's food is cooked to its specific standards.</p>

    <h3>Hospital and Institutional Kitchens</h3>
    <p>Hospital kitchens serving 300+ meals per day benefit enormously from combi ovens. The retherm (reheating) mode is critical — cook-chill operations can reheat plated meals in combi mode without drying them out. Steam mode preserves nutrients in vegetables. HACCP data logging provides the documentation required for food safety audits. Typical setup: two 20-tray combi ovens for a 500-bed hospital.</p>

    <h3>Airline Catering</h3>
    <p>Combi ovens are standard in airline catering kitchens. They are used for bulk cooking, blast chilling prep, and reheating. The programmable multi-step cooking and HACCP logging are essential for the strict food safety requirements of airline catering.</p>

    <h2>11. Installation Requirements</h2>

    <h3>Water Softener and Drain Requirements</h3>
    <p>This is often overlooked by first-time combi oven buyers in India, and it is critical.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Water supply:</strong> A combi oven needs a dedicated cold water inlet (standard 3/4" BSP connection). Water pressure should be 1.5–4 bar.</li>
      <li><strong>Water softener:</strong> This is <strong>not optional</strong> in India. Indian water is typically very hard (200–500 ppm TDS in most cities). Hard water causes limescale buildup in the steam generator, which will damage the oven within months. Every combi oven installation in India requires a water softener. Budget ₹15,000–₹40,000 for a suitable water softener plus ongoing salt costs (₹500–₹1,000/month).</li>
      <li><strong>Drain:</strong> A combi oven needs a floor drain within 1–2 metres. The drain line should be minimum 50mm diameter. Steam condensate and self-cleaning waste water need to drain freely. Some ovens also need a drain for the cavity (gravity drain or pump, depending on installation height).</li>
      <li><strong>Water filtration:</strong> In addition to softening, a sediment filter is recommended to remove particulates that can clog valves.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Ventilation Requirements</h3>
    <p>A combi oven generates significant steam and heat. Proper ventilation is essential:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Exhaust hood:</strong> A commercial <a href="/blog/commercial-exhaust-hood">exhaust hood</a> is required above the combi oven. Size the hood to extend 150mm beyond the oven on all open sides.</li>
      <li><strong>Exhaust capacity:</strong> Minimum 1,500–3,000 m³/hr for a 6-10 tray unit; 3,000–5,000 m³/hr for a 20-tray unit.</li>
      <li><strong>Condensation hood:</strong> Some premium combi ovens (like the Rational iCombi Pro) offer an optional condensation hood that captures up to 80% of steam exhaust, significantly reducing ventilation requirements. This is useful in Indian kitchens where retrofitting exhaust ductwork is expensive.</li>
      <li><strong>Clearance:</strong> Maintain minimum 50mm clearance on sides and rear for air circulation. Check brand-specific requirements — some need more.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Electrical Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>6-tray electric:</strong> 10–12 kW, typically requires a dedicated 3-phase 32A breaker</li>
      <li><strong>10-tray electric:</strong> 18–22 kW, typically requires a dedicated 3-phase 40A breaker</li>
      <li><strong>20-tray electric:</strong> 36–44 kW, typically requires a dedicated 3-phase 63A breaker</li>
      <li>All installations need proper earthing and should be done by a licensed electrician</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>12. Self-Cleaning Features</h2>
    <p>One of the biggest advantages of a combi oven over traditional ovens is automatic self-cleaning. Here is how it works:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>How it works:</strong> The oven heats water and specialised cleaning detergent to high temperature, sprays it across all interior surfaces, rinses, and dries. The entire cycle takes 30–90 minutes depending on the cleaning level selected.</li>
      <li><strong>Cleaning tablets/liquid:</strong> Most brands use proprietary cleaning chemicals. Rational uses iCare tablets (~₹80–120 per tablet, one per cleaning cycle). Unox uses ROTOR.Klean liquid. Budget ₹3,000–₹6,000 per month for cleaning chemicals (daily cleaning).</li>
      <li><strong>Why it matters:</strong> A combi oven that is not cleaned daily will suffer from grease buildup, impaired steam quality, off-flavours, and reduced lifespan. Automatic cleaning ensures consistency even with rotating kitchen staff. Manual cleaning of a combi oven is time-consuming and often done poorly.</li>
      <li><strong>Cleaning schedule:</strong> Run a full cleaning cycle at the end of each working day. Some kitchens also run a quick rinse between cooking different food types (e.g., after cooking fish, before baking pastries).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For general oven maintenance tips, see our <a href="/blog/commercial-oven-maintenance">Commercial Oven Maintenance</a> guide.</p>

    <h2>13. Running Cost Analysis</h2>
    <p>Understanding the total cost of ownership is crucial. Here is a monthly running cost breakdown for a 10-tray electric combi oven operating 8 hours per day in an Indian commercial kitchen:</p>

